Respiratory mechanics and pulmonary function testing 

Wednesday, May 10, 2017 

3:05 PM 

Briefly describe the mechanisms for controlling airway diameter 

-Contraction/relaxation of constrictor and dilator skeletal muscles attached to upper airway wall (above laryngeal glottis); the relaxation of dilator muscles during sleep or anesthesia can lead to heavy snoring and upper airway collapse (obstructive sleep apnea)  

-Contraction/relaxation of circular smooth muscle cells in the wall of intrathoracic airways (bronchi/bronchioles); spiraling smooth muscle cells are in the bronchi and circumferentially-oriented smooth muscle cells are in the bronchioles 

 

Note that airway smooth muscle cells are usually in a relaxed state (with little contractile tone), so little further relaxation is possible 

 

How is intraluminal airway diameter controlled? 

Intrathoracic airway smooth muscle cells receives acetylcholine from parasympathetic postganglionic nerve endings, which bind to muscarinic cholinergic receptors on the airway of the smooth muscle cell to cause smooth muscle contraction which decreases diameter.  

 

The intrathoracic airway smooth muscles receive little sympathetic innervation, but are richly-supplied with non-innervated beta-2 adrenergic receptors which can be stimulated by circulating adrenaline. This causes the relaxation of airway smooth muscle cells which widens the intraluminal airway.  

 

These smooth muscles can be stimulated to contract by a wide range of inflammatory stimulators such as histamine and cytokines, playing an important role in airway diseases such as asthma and mucus accumulation.  

 

Note that the intrathoracic airway diameter mechanically increases when lung volume increases, and vice-versa. This is crucial, as small obstructed airways are kept open in diseases such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease where these patients often have overinflated lungs (pulmonary hyperinflation).  

 

How can an airway be obstructed? 

 

Briefly describe the function of airway diameter changes in normal respiration. 

-Filtering, warming/cooling and humidification of inhaled air are all defensive functions to protect the delicate alveoli 

-Reflex narrowing of the airways in response to inhaled smoke improves the efficiency of airway filtration, such that less noxious material reaches the alveoli 

-During stress, the release of circulating adrenaline favors bronchodilation and thus facilitates ventilation 

 

Briefly describe the effect of airway diameter on airway resistance and how changes in airway resistance alter dynamic lung compliance 

-As air moves along the airways, it has to overcome frictional resistance between moving air molecules and the inside surfaces of the airway 

-By Ohm's Law, Alveolar pressure = Airflow x Airway resistance 

 

Note that airflow depends on airway diameter and geometry. The effect of radius on resistance is much greater when airflow is non-streamlined (non-laminar), with transitional and turbulent flow: 

 

 

Lung compliance and Pendelluft 

Pendulluft is the movement of air from one lung region to another after airflow at the mouth has ceased. This is due to one lung region inflating more easily than the other, which will therefore have greater elastic recoil pressure thereby driving air into the less inflated lung regions.  

 

Dynamic lung compliance is measured by dividing tidal volume (volume of air inhaled per breath) by the difference in intrapleural pressure just before the start and at the end of inspiration. However, during pendulluft, the overall lung elastic recoil pressure measured at the mouth drops. This causes the change in intrapleural pressure during inspiration to be overestimated, and thus dynamic lung compliance is underestimated. This effect can be used to detect the early stages of small airway obstructions in progressive lung diseases.  

 

Briefly describe the factors that determine the differences in the shape of the pulmonary compliance curve in inspiration and expiration 

Compliance is a measure of distensibility, computed from a pressure-volume curve by Compliance = Change in Volume/Change in Pressure. This is mainly determined by elastin and collagen fibers, and surface tension (surfactant). 

 

 

 

Differences between the inspiratory and expiratory curves are called hysteresis. This is largely caused by the increased release of lung surfactant into the alveolar fluid as the lungs are inflated. Removing the alveolar air-liquid interface by filling the lungs with saline essentially removes the hysteresis.  

 

Briefly describe the four lung volumes and four capacities and their evaluation using spirometry 

 

Spirometry is used to clinically assess lung function, typically involving maximum inspiration to the maximum lung volume followed by a forced maximal expiration to the minimum lung volume possible. Spirometers are often used to record changes in lung volume over time (called a spirogram).  

Tidal volume is typically 7ml/kg maintained throughout life (from 3kg infant to 70kg adult) 

Minute ventilation = Tidal volume x Respiratory frequency 

 

Residual volume, functional residual capacity and total lung capacity 

-Residual volume is trapped gas and cannot be measured by simple spirometry (This normally = around 1.2L and cannot be exhaled because the small intrathoracic airways progressively narrow as lung volume decreases, until it shuts off at this residual volume with air still in the subtended alveoli.) Residual volume increases if airways are already obstructed.  

Note that TLC includes RV. 

 

Briefly describe spirometric assessment of obstructive and restrictive ventilatory impairments.  

There are two clinical tests commonly used in diagnosing and assessing respiratory disorders: 

-Forced Vital Capacity (FVC): forced expiratory volume following maximal inhalation 

-Forced expiratory volume in 1st second (FEV1): maximum volume expelled in 1st second of a maximal forced expiration 

Measurements of FVC and FEV1 are compared against tables of predicted values by gender, age, body size. Evidence of airway obstruction presents if FEV1 < 75%.  

 

Obstructive disorder: FEV1 falls but FVC often is normal, thus FEV1/FVC < 0.8 

Restrictive disorder (unable to maximally expand the lungs):  FEV1 and FVC are both reduced relatively equally, FEV1/FVC does not go below 0.8.  

 

Briefly describe the forces that generate negative intrapleural pressure when the lung is at functional residual capacity and predict the direction the lung and chest wall will move if air is introduced into the pleural cavity. 

Intrapleural pressure is normally negative relative to atmospheric pressure when the respiratory muscles are relaxed, because the lungs are always trying to collapse away from the chest wall. The relaxed chest wall attempts to assume a lung volume of around 60% of the vital capacity where it has no elastic recoil. Above 60% the chest wall attempts to collapse (increasing intrapleural pressure), and below 60% the chest wall attempts to expand (decreasing intrapleural pressure). The lung volume where the collapsing recoil of the lungs is equal and opposite to the expansive recoil of the chest wall is called the functional residual capacity, and normally equals the lung volume after a normal quiet tidal expiration.  

Briefly describe the physiological mechanisms that produce subjective shortness of breath 

Dyspnea can be postulated to be caused by many mechanisms, including: 

-Stimulation of peripheral and central chemoreceptors by decreased pO2, pH and increased pCO2.  

-Stimulation of vagal lung receptors  

-Stimulation of mechanoreceptors in the respiratory muscles 

-Increased awareness of normal breathing 

 

There is a variety of distinct conscious sensations that can be involved in dyspnea, including air hunger, respiratory effort, tightening in the chest, and a feeling of suffocation.  

 

Dyspnea can occur in health (eg during intense exercise), and in many diseases eg those affecting the lungs, heart and neuromuscular system.
